{"title": "Signal handler not safe in threaded context", "description": "signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, ...) is called in _run_single_lens_streaming and _send_and_stream, but signal handlers can only be set in the main thread. If these methods are ever called from a non-main thread (e.g., during review() which uses threading), this will raise ValueError. The review() method itself doesn't hit this because it uses _run_lens_oneshot, but any future refactor could trigger it.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "", "new_string": "", "invariant": "signal.signal() must only be called from the main thread"}

{"title": "Temp file written to working_dir may be world-readable", "description": "NamedTemporaryFile creates files in working_dir with default permissions. System prompts containing sensitive analysis context are written to disk in a potentially shared directory. On Unix systems, the default umask may allow other users to read these files before they are deleted.", "severity": "P1", "old_string": "tmp = tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(
            mode="w", suffix=".md", delete=False, encoding="utf-8",
            dir=str(self.working_dir))", "new_string": "tmp = tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(
            mode="w", suffix=".md", delete=False, encoding="utf-8")", "invariant": "Sensitive data should not be written to user-controlled directories with default permissions; use system temp dir instead"}

{"title": "Path traversal via issue file field in _resolve_file", "description": "_resolve_file joins user/model-supplied 'file' fields from issues.json with working_dir without sanitizing path traversal sequences. A malicious or malformed issue with file='../../etc/passwd' would resolve outside the working directory, and _heal_fix_one would read/snapshot that file. _heal_restore could then overwrite it.", "severity": "P0", "old_string": "    def _resolve_file(self, arg):
        """Resolve a file path relative to working_dir."""
        if not arg:
            return None
        path = pathlib.Path(arg)
        if not path.is_absolute():
            path = self.working_dir / path
        return path if path.exists() else None", "new_string": "    def _resolve_file(self, arg):
        """Resolve a file path relative to working_dir. Rejects traversal outside."""
        if not arg:
            return None
        path = pathlib.Path(arg)
        if not path.is_absolute():
            path = self.working_dir / path
        try:
            resolved = path.resolve()
            if not str(resolved).startswith(str(self.working_dir.resolve())):
                return None
        except (OSError, ValueError):
            return None
        return resolved if resolved.exists() else None", "invariant": "All file operations must be confined to the working directory"}

{"title": "Race condition: temp file deleted before subprocess reads it", "description": "In ClaudeInterface.call() and call_checked(), the temp file containing the system prompt is created, closed, and then passed to subprocess.run(). The finally block deletes it. However, there's no guarantee the subprocess has opened the file before the parent continues. On fast systems or under load, if subprocess.run raises an unexpected exception before the subprocess starts, the file is deleted. More critically, in call_streaming(), the caller is responsible for deleting tmp_path but the Popen may not have opened it yet.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "", "new_string": "", "invariant": "Temp files passed to subprocesses must remain available until the subprocess has consumed them"}

{"title": "Unbounded file read into memory", "description": "Multiple places read entire files with read_text() without size limits: _heal_grep_context, _enrich, _run_single_lens_streaming, _build_message, review(). A very large file (e.g., multi-GB log) could exhaust memory. Only _heal_verify has a truncation ([:8000]).", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "", "new_string": "", "invariant": "File reads should be bounded to prevent OOM on unexpectedly large files"}

{"title": "TOCTOU race in _heal_fix_one snapshot/restore", "description": "In _heal_fix_one, the file is snapshotted before the fix, then Claude edits it via tools, then the user reviews. If another process modifies the file between snapshot and restore (on rejection), the restore silently overwrites those external changes. The file_mtimes drift check in _cmd_heal only warns at load time, not during the fix cycle.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "", "new_string": "", "invariant": "File restore should verify the file hasn't been modified by a third party since the fix was applied"}

{"title": "Integer overflow on string ID hash", "description": "In _normalize_issue, string IDs are hashed with abs(hash(raw_id)) % 10000. Python's hash() can return negative values and abs(hash()) can collide for different strings within 10000 values. Two different issues could get the same integer ID, causing one to shadow the other in _heal_pick_issues lookups.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "            issue["id"] = abs(hash(raw_id)) % 10000", "new_string": "            issue["id"] = abs(hash(raw_id)) % 100000", "invariant": "Issue IDs must be unique within a scan; hash space should be large enough to minimize collisions"}

{"title": "review() exit code logic is inverted", "description": "review() returns 1 (indicating issues found) whenever any lens produces output, but lens output is always expected when analysis succeeds. The docstring says '0=clean, 1=issues', but any successful analysis will return 1. Exit code 0 (clean) only happens when all lenses return empty strings, which indicates failure, not cleanliness.", "severity": "P1", "old_string": "        # Exit code: 1 if any results found content, 0 if empty
        has_findings = any(v.strip() for v in all_results.values())
        return 1 if has_findings else 0", "new_string": "        # Exit code: 0 on success (findings written), 1 if no analysis produced
        has_findings = any(v.strip() for v in all_results.values())
        return 0 if has_findings else 1", "invariant": "Exit codes should follow Unix convention: 0=success, non-zero=failure"}

{"title": "ClaudeBackend.send() uses raw bytes but Popen opened without text mode", "description": "ClaudeBackend.send() opens Popen without text=True or encoding, then writes message.encode('utf-8') to stdin and decodes stdout lines manually. But ClaudeInterface.call_streaming() opens Popen WITH text=True and encoding='utf-8'. The inconsistency means ClaudeBackend.send() handles bytes, risking encoding issues on Windows where the default encoding isn't UTF-8.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "            self.proc = subprocess.Popen(
                cmd,
                stdin=subprocess.PIPE,
                stdout=subprocess.PIPE,
                stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL,
                env=env,
                cwd=self.working_dir,
            )

            try:
                self.proc.stdin.write(message.encode("utf-8"))
                self.proc.stdin.close()
            except BrokenPipeError:
                return

            for raw_line in self.proc.stdout:
                yield raw_line.decode("utf-8", errors="replace")", "new_string": "            self.proc = subprocess.Popen(
                cmd,
                stdin=subprocess.PIPE,
                stdout=subprocess.PIPE,
                stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL,
                text=True,
                encoding="utf-8",
                errors="replace",
                env=env,
                cwd=self.working_dir,
            )

            try:
                self.proc.stdin.write(message)
                self.proc.stdin.close()
            except BrokenPipeError:
                return

            for raw_line in self.proc.stdout:
                yield raw_line", "invariant": "Subprocess I/O encoding should be consistent across all call sites"}

{"title": "Semaphore in review() not released on thread exception before acquire", "description": "In review(), the threading pattern acquires the semaphore inside _run, but if the thread function throws before sem.acquire() (which can't happen in current code but is fragile), or if run_one throws after acquire but the finally in _run handles release. Actually the real issue is that run_one exceptions are silently swallowed — result defaults to empty string but thread exceptions are lost.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "        threads = []
        for fpath in files:
            for lens in lenses:
                def _run(f=fpath, l=lens):
                    sem.acquire()
                    try:
                        run_one(f, l)
                    finally:
                        sem.release()
                t = threading.Thread(target=_run)
                t.start()
                threads.append(t)", "new_string": "        threads = []
        for fpath in files:
            for lens in lenses:
                def _run(f=fpath, l=lens):
                    sem.acquire()
                    try:
                        run_one(f, l)
                    except Exception:
                        with lock:
                            all_results[(f.name, l)] = ""
                            done[0] += 1
                    finally:
                        sem.release()
                t = threading.Thread(target=_run, daemon=True)
                t.start()
                threads.append(t)", "invariant": "Thread exceptions must be caught to ensure progress counter stays accurate and semaphore is always released"}

{"title": "build_cmd falls back to --system-prompt (shell injection risk)", "description": "ClaudeBackend.build_cmd() falls back to passing self.system_prompt via --system-prompt command line argument when there's no prompt_file and no session_id. This puts potentially large user-influenced text directly on the command line, which could cause issues with shell escaping or argument length limits. Additionally, the code path is unreachable in current code (send() always passes prompt_file), but if build_cmd is called directly it's dangerous.", "severity": "P1", "old_string": "        if self.session_id:
            cmd += ["--resume", self.session_id]
        elif prompt_file:
            cmd += ["--system-prompt-file", prompt_file]
        else:
            cmd += ["--system-prompt", self.system_prompt]
        return cmd", "new_string": "        if self.session_id:
            cmd += ["--resume", self.session_id]
        elif prompt_file:
            cmd += ["--system-prompt-file", prompt_file]
        else:
            raise ValueError("build_cmd requires either session_id or prompt_file; "
                             "passing system prompt via command line is unsafe")
        return cmd", "invariant": "System prompts must be passed via file, never via command-line arguments"}

{"title": "Missing thread safety on self.queued_files", "description": "self.queued_files is a plain list that is read and modified in _enrich(), _build_message(), _cmd_read(), and _cmd_clear() without any locking. While current usage is single-threaded in the REPL loop, review() uses threading and _run_lens_oneshot. If future code accesses queued_files from threads, this would be a race condition.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "", "new_string": "", "invariant": "Shared mutable state should be protected by locks if any code path involves threading"}

{"title": "Regex pattern in _save_deep_finding can fail on special characters", "description": "The regex pattern uses re.escape on lens_name.upper() but the replacement string (new_section.strip()) is not escaped for regex special characters in re.sub. If the output text contains backslash sequences like \1 or \g<0>, re.sub will interpret them as backreferences, corrupting the saved findings.", "severity": "P1", "old_string": "            if re.search(pattern, existing, re.DOTALL):
                updated = re.sub(pattern, new_section.strip(), existing,
                                 count=1, flags=re.DOTALL)", "new_string": "            if re.search(pattern, existing, re.DOTALL):
                updated = re.sub(pattern, lambda _: new_section.strip(), existing,
                                 count=1, flags=re.DOTALL)", "invariant": "re.sub replacement strings must not contain unescaped backreferences when the replacement is dynamic text"}

{"title": "Session.load trusts arbitrary JSON from disk", "description": "Session.load() reads and trusts arbitrary fields from a JSON file in ~/.prism_sessions/ without validation. A crafted session file could set model to an arbitrary string (bypassing the haiku/sonnet/opus validation in _cmd_model), set negative token counts, or set session_id to a malicious value passed to --resume.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "        self.session_id = data.get("session_id")
        self.model = data.get("model", "sonnet")
        self.total_input_tokens = data.get("total_input_tokens", 0)
        self.total_output_tokens = data.get("total_output_tokens", 0)
        self.total_cost_usd = data.get("total_cost_usd", 0.0)
        self.turn_count = data.get("turn_count", 0)
        return True", "new_string": "        self.session_id = data.get("session_id")
        model = data.get("model", "sonnet")
        if model not in ("haiku", "sonnet", "opus"):
            model = "sonnet"
        self.model = model
        self.total_input_tokens = max(0, int(data.get("total_input_tokens", 0)))
        self.total_output_tokens = max(0, int(data.get("total_output_tokens", 0)))
        self.total_cost_usd = max(0.0, float(data.get("total_cost_usd", 0.0)))
        self.turn_count = max(0, int(data.get("turn_count", 0)))
        return True", "invariant": "Data loaded from disk must be validated before use"}

{"title": "_cmd_heal registered as /fix but docstring says /fix", "description": "The command /fix is mapped to _cmd_heal handler. The _cmd_heal docstring references '/fix' which is correct, but the actual method name '_cmd_heal' is misleading vs the registered command '/fix'. More importantly, there's no /heal command registered, so the old method name is just confusing, not a bug.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "", "new_string": "", "invariant": "Method names should match their registered command names for maintainability"}

{"title": "Cost field extraction inconsistency", "description": "In _handle_result and _run_single_lens_streaming, cost is read as data.get('total_cost_usd', data.get('cost_usd', 0)). If the CLI changes the field name or returns both fields, the wrong one could be used. More critically, if total_cost_usd is present but set to None (not 0), the isinstance check passes None through and += fails.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "        cost = data.get("total_cost_usd", data.get("cost_usd", 0))
        if isinstance(cost, (int, float)):
            self.session.total_cost_usd += cost

        self.session.turn_count += 1", "new_string": "        cost = data.get("total_cost_usd") or data.get("cost_usd") or 0
        if isinstance(cost, (int, float)):
            self.session.total_cost_usd += cost

        self.session.turn_count += 1", "invariant": "Nullable numeric fields from external sources should use falsy-or fallback, not nested .get defaults"}

{"title": "_show_inline_diff resets counter mid-stream causing infinite loop", "description": "When the user types 'y' to show the full diff, `shown` is reset to 0. But the loop continues iterating over `diff` from where it left off. If the remaining lines exceed 60 again, the prompt fires again. If the user keeps pressing 'y', this works but is confusing. The real bug: resetting shown=0 means the 60-line gate will fire every 60 lines forever, not 'show the rest'.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "                if ans != "y":
                    break
                shown = 0  # Reset counter for the rest", "new_string": "                if ans != "y":
                    break
                shown = -len(diff)  # Effectively disable the gate for the rest", "invariant": "A 'show all' confirmation should disable further pagination, not restart the counter"}
